Prosper Loan Data Analysis¶

by (Preethi Philip)¶

Introduction¶

The Prosper Loan data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Original data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.But I have selected few features for my analysis. So my data set contains 84853 Rows and 14 Columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested to predict what features are best for predicting the BorrowerRate for the loan and how Prosper rating, employment status, MonthlyLoanPayment and other features associates with various metrics in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The Original Dataset contains so many variables.But I have selected few features for my analysis.

'Term','LoanStatus','LoanOriginalAmount','BorrowerRate','ProsperRating(Alpha)','DebtToIncomeRatio','ProsperScore','EmploymentStatus', 'StatedMonthlyIncome','Occupation','LoanOriginationDate','TotalProsperLoans','MonthlyLoanPayment','CreditScoreRangeLower',

1. Loan Status¶

The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.

In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
# Return the Series having unique values
count = df['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
loan_order = count.index
# see the counts for Loan Status
sb.countplot(data = df , x='LoanStatus', color=base_color,order = loan_order)
# Labeling the axes
plt.xlabel('LoanStatus')
plt.ylabel('count')
plt.title('LoanStatus')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

Observation¶

Most of the loans are current loan. And the other big part is the Completed loan.The number of past due and cancelled are quite low.

In [46]:
def myRegplot(df,xVar,yVar,x_jitter = 0.35,y_jitter=0):
#     plot dimensions
    plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
    sb.regplot(data = df , x = xVar, y = yVar,x_jitter = 0.35, scatter_kws={'s':4},line_kws = {'color':'maroon'});
#     add title and labels
    plt.title(f'Relationship Between {yVar} and {xVar}'.title(), fontsize = 14, weight = 'bold')
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
    plt.ylabel(yVar.title(),fontsize = 10, weight = "bold")
    
myRegplot(df, 'LoanOriginationYear','LoanOriginalAmount')

Observation¶

At the beginning the Loan Origination Amount is less comparatively. And Regplot shows an increase in rates in the coming year

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Borrowers who have the highest credit score and prosper score will have the lowest interest rates. The higher the loan amount, the lower the borrower's rate. Full-time part-time employers and retirees have a high Prosper score on completed loans. Outside the major variables of interest, I found that the loan amount is positively related to the stated monthly income, which makes sense as borrowers with higher monthly income can lend more money.

Conclusions¶

The Prosper Loan data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.But I have selected few features for my analysis. So my data set contains 84853 Rows and 14 Columns.The difficulties I had with the data were mainly due to understanding the variables and selecting the appropriate ones to analyze. I had to do some initial exploration of the data. I chose 'BorrowerRate' as my target variable as this number is very important for a potential borrower.

After setting the targeted variable, we can move on to the next step and start exploring the relationship between the variables, especially those related to our target variable.

The strongest relationships I have found are the Prosper Score vs Lone status and interest rate. Evaluate the Borrower's Credit rating and Employement status . This feature has been shown to be effective in predicting whether or not a default loan will occur. So Prosper can use this score to determine the borrower's interest rate. Outside the major variables of interest, I found that the loan amount is positively related to the stated monthly income, which makes sense as borrowers with higher monthly income can lend more money.
